                        heading: 'The Crisis of Land',
                        body: '<p>By the mid-second century BC, Rome faces a structural crisis. Prolonged military campaigns abroad have devastated the Italian peasantry: smallholders who serve as legionaries return to find their farms absorbed into vast senatorial estates worked by slave labour. The result is a growing class of landless citizens who cannot qualify for military service under the property-based Servian system, and who drift into Rome as an increasingly volatile urban poor.</p><p>Tiberius Gracchus, tribune of the plebs in 133 BC, proposes the <span style="font-family:\'Roboto Mono\',monospace;font-style:italic">lex Sempronia agraria</span>. The bill is not revolutionary in principle: it seeks to enforce the existing legal limit of 500 <span style="font-family:\'Roboto Mono\',monospace;font-style:italic">iugera</span> of <span style="font-family:\'Roboto Mono\',monospace;font-style:italic">ager publicus</span> per individual, with an additional 250 per son, redistributing the excess in small allotments to landless citizens. A three-man commission is to oversee the redistribution.</p>'
