                        heading: 'The First Political Murder',
                        body: '<p>When Tiberius stands for a second consecutive tribunate — itself a breach of convention, though probably not of law — the Senate meets in the Temple of Fides. The consul Scaevola refuses to act against Tiberius without due process. Publius Cornelius Scipio Nasica, the <span style="font-family:\'Roboto Mono\',monospace;font-style:italic">pontifex maximus</span>, declares "let those who wish to save the Republic follow me," wraps his toga over his head in a ritual gesture, and leads a group of senators and their clients to the Capitol. They beat Tiberius and some three hundred of his supporters to death with clubs and chair legs.</p><p>The significance cannot be overstated. For over three centuries, Roman politics has operated without political murder. Disputes are resolved through constitutional mechanisms — vetoes, elections, senatorial debate — or through the social pressure of <span style="font-family:\'Roboto Mono\',monospace;font-style:italic">mos maiorum</span>. Nasica\'s action shatters this. Violence is now an available political tool, and the senatorial class has demonstrated its willingness to use it.</p>'
