                        heading: 'The senatus consultum ultimum',
                        body: '<p>When Gaius fails to win a third tribunate and his political position weakens, a confrontation develops over the repeal of one of his laws. In the violence that follows, a lictor of the consul Opimius is killed. The Senate responds with a decree that has no precedent: the <span style="font-family:\'Roboto Mono\',monospace;font-style:italic">senatus consultum ultimum</span>, instructing the consuls to "see to it that the Republic suffers no harm" — <span style="font-family:\'Roboto Mono\',monospace;font-style:italic">videant consules ne quid res publica detrimenti capiat</span>.</p><p>This formula effectively suspends the normal protections of <span style="font-family:\'Roboto Mono\',monospace;font-style:italic">provocatio</span> — the citizen\'s right of appeal against summary execution. Consul Opimius treats the decree as authority to use military force within the city. Gaius, cornered on the Aventine, orders a slave to kill him. Opimius then massacres some 3,000 of Gaius\'s supporters without trial.</p>'
