            evidence: 'Nasica\u2019s killing of Tiberius in 133 BC was the first political murder in Republican history. The consul Scaevola refused to act, showing that even some senators recognised the illegitimacy of violence. The SCU of 121 BC against Gaius had no constitutional basis \u2014 the Senate was an advisory body, not a legislative one. Opimius\u2019s massacre of 3,000 supporters of Gaius went unpunished. The Senate\u2019s failure to punish Nasica established impunity for political violence. Cicero later relied on the SCU to justify executing the Catilinarian conspirators in 63 BC, and was himself exiled for it \u2014 showing that the legality of the SCU was never resolved.',
            modelParagraph: '<p>The Senate\u2019s responsibility for introducing political violence into the late Republic is difficult to deny. Tiberius Gracchus broke <em>mos maiorum</em> by deposing Octavius and seeking re-election, but he did not kill anyone. It was Scipio Nasica, the <em>pontifex maximus</em>, who led senators to beat Tiberius and some three hundred supporters to death with clubs and chair legs on the Capitol in 133 BC \u2014 the first political murder in over three centuries of Republican history. The Senate\u2019s response was not to punish Nasica but to send him discreetly to Asia. Twelve years later, the Senate went further: the <em>senatus consultum ultimum</em> of 121 BC gave consul Opimius a blank cheque to use military force against Gaius Gracchus and his supporters, resulting in approximately 3,000 deaths without trial. The SCU had no constitutional basis \u2014 the Senate\u2019s decrees were advisory, not legally binding \u2014 yet it became the Republic\u2019s preferred instrument for eliminating political opponents, used again against Saturninus in 100 BC and the Catilinarian conspirators in 63 BC. The Gracchi may have broken the rules, but the Senate broke the peace. And once political murder was established as an available tactic, the precedent could never be unlearned: it escalated through Sulla\u2019s proscriptions to the civil wars that destroyed the Republic entirely.</p>'
