            evidence: 'The deposition of Octavius (133 BC), the murder of Tiberius by Nasica (133 BC), and the SCU against Gaius (121 BC) are the three key precedents. The <em>lex Sempronia agraria</em> addressed the agrarian crisis that the Senate had ignored \u2014 showing structural causes preceded the Gracchi. Marius\u2019s reform of 107 BC created the professional army loyal to commanders. Sulla\u2019s march on Rome (88 BC) was a qualitative escalation beyond anything the Gracchan period produced. Cicero\u2019s <em>De Re Publica</em> presents Tiberius as the beginning of Rome\u2019s division, while Cicero\u2019s letters in the 50s and 40s BC reveal a Republic in terminal decline from causes far beyond the Gracchi.',
            modelParagraph: '<p>To call the Gracchi the \u201croot cause\u201d of the Republic\u2019s fall is to confuse the catalyst with the cause. The <em>lex Sempronia agraria</em> of 133 BC addressed a crisis that the Senate had ignored for decades: the displacement of smallholding peasants by slave-worked <em>latifundia</em>, a structural consequence of imperial expansion that no individual could have prevented. The Gracchi did not create this crisis. What they created were the <em>precedents</em> through which it expressed itself politically: the deposition of a tribune, political murder, legislation that bypassed the Senate, and the <em>senatus consultum ultimum</em>. But precedents are not causes. Marius\u2019s army reforms of 107 BC, which created soldiers loyal to their commander rather than the state, were structurally more significant than anything the Gracchi did. Sulla\u2019s march on Rome in 88 BC was a qualitative escalation that the Gracchi could not have imagined. Caesar\u2019s crossing of the Rubicon in 49 BC was the act that ended the Republic in practice, and it was driven by personal <em>dignitas</em> and military power, not by Gracchan precedents. Cicero\u2019s <em>De Re Publica</em> blames Tiberius for dividing the state, but Cicero\u2019s own letters in the 50s BC reveal a Republic dying from causes far deeper than any single reformer\u2019s actions. The Gracchi are where the story begins, but they are not why it ends.</p>'
